  "response": "Donald Trump's experiences and social standing during his high school years have been discussed in various accounts, including his own statements and biographies. Here's an overview based on available information:\n\n### Education Background\n- **New York Military Academy (NMA):** At the age of 13, Donald Trump was sent by his parents to the New York Military Academy, a private boarding school in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York. He attended NMA from 1964 to 1966.\n\n### Trump\u2019s Perspective\n- **Leadership and Excellence:** In interviews and his autobiography, *The Art of the Deal*, Donald Trump has portrayed his time at NMA as formative, emphasizing leadership roles and academic success. He has often highlighted his involvement in sports and extracurricular activities, suggesting a positive and active school experience.\n\n### Biographical Insights\n- **Mixed Accounts:** Biographers and those who have studied Trump's early life provide a more nuanced picture. For instance:\n  - **Peter Knobler**, author of *Donald Trump: Master Apprentice*, notes that Trump was confident and ambitious but doesn't specifically detail his popularity.\n  - **John Updike**'s portrayal in his unfinished novel *Roger & Me*, while fictional, hints at Trump\u2019s assertive personality traits developed during his school years.\n\n### Peer and Teacher Accounts\n- **Limited Public Records:** There is limited public documentation or detailed accounts from classmates or teachers about Trump\u2019s social standing during his high school years. As a result, much of the narrative relies on Trump's own descriptions and selective biographical information.\n\n### Conclusion\nWhile Donald Trump has depicted his high school experience at the New York Military Academy as successful and leadership-oriented, comprehensive external accounts regarding his popularity among peers are scarce. The available information suggests that he was confident and active, but specific details about his social standing\u2014whether he was broadly popular or more of a solitary figure\u2014are not extensively documented in public records.",
